"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Deuteronomy chapters 3–4
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-deuteronomy-3-4-fill.py

Key decisions:
- Ch 3: Joshua as explicit type of Christ (same name; leads into rest Moses could not)
- Ch 3: Moses excluded from land read as shadow of vicarious consequence, not full atonement
- Ch 3: Rephaim/giant victory = shadow of Christ's defeat of all hostile powers
- Ch 4: Aniconic Horeb theophany (no form, only voice) connects to John 1:18 and Col 1:15
- Ch 4: ʾên ʿôd monotheism connects to Paul's christological differentiation of the Shema
- Ch 4: Cities of refuge read as type of Christ per Heb 6:18
- Directness levels: direct (NT explicit citation), type, shadow, theme, revelation of God
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

DEUTERONOMY = {
"3": {
"1": "<p>The divine warrior theme: YHWH delivers Og of Bashan into Israel&apos;s hands as he delivered Sihon. This pattern of God fighting for his people — not Israel&apos;s military prowess winning the day — is the Old Testament&apos;s recurring testimony to a God who acts in history on behalf of those he has chosen. The NT presents Christ as the ultimate divine warrior who defeats the last and greatest enemies: sin, death, and the powers (1 Cor 15:24–26; Col 2:15).</p>",
"2": "<p>The &quot;do not fear&quot; command paired with divine assurance — &quot;I have given him into your hand&quot; — is the covenant pattern of promised victory before the battle is fought. This proleptic assurance mirrors the NT structure where Christ&apos;s victory over death is declared before the believer&apos;s own death is faced (John 16:33: &quot;In the world you will have tribulation. But take heart; I have overcome the world&quot;). The same God who assured Moses assures those united to Christ.</p>",
"3": "<p>YHWH gives Og into Israel&apos;s hands — the complete subjugation of a hostile king with no survivors. As a revelation of God&apos;s faithfulness: what he promises, he delivers. The New Testament presents Christ as the one in whom all of God&apos;s promises are &quot;yes and amen&quot; (2 Cor 1:20) — every word of assurance spoken in the Old Testament finds its fulfillment in him.</p>",
"4": "<p>Sixty fortified cities taken — the scope of the victory exceeds any natural expectation. The comprehensive nature of the divine warrior&apos;s triumph foreshadows the unlimited scope of Christ&apos;s victory: &quot;All authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me&quot; (Matt 28:18). No fortress of human power or spiritual opposition can withstand the one to whom ultimate authority belongs.</p>",
"5": "<p>High walls, gates, and bars — the most formidable military defenses of the ancient world — fall before YHWH&apos;s people. The prophetic tradition picks up this imagery: &quot;I will break in pieces the gates of bronze and cut through the bars of iron&quot; (Isa 45:2). Christ extends this victory to the gates of Hades itself: &quot;the gates of hell shall not prevail against it&quot; (Matt 16:18). A theme running from this verse through to the unlocking of every stronghold in Christ.</p>",
"6": "<p>The herem (devotion to destruction) applied to Og&apos;s cities — the most theologically difficult aspect of the conquest narratives. The herem reveals the holiness of God&apos;s judgment against Canaanite evil accumulated over four centuries (Gen 15:16). The New Testament does not abolish divine judgment but relocates its center: at the cross, Christ bears the judgment himself (2 Cor 5:21; Gal 3:13), exhausting its claim. Revelation 19 restores the divine-warrior imagery for the final judgment, but the cross stands between the conquest herem and the eschatological herem as the place where judgment was absorbed.</p>",
"7": "<p>Livestock and plunder kept — in contrast to the full herem applied to persons. The distinction between what is consecrated to destruction and what is legitimately claimed as provision reflects the covenant community&apos;s practical sustenance. As a revelation of God&apos;s character: he provides for his people&apos;s needs even within the severity of holy war, a theme the NT develops in Christ as the one who provides abundantly for those who follow him (John 10:10).</p>",
"8": "<p>The territory east of the Jordan taken from the Amorite kings — the first installment of the promised land. The land as YHWH&apos;s gift, received through combat, is a type of the inheritance believers receive in Christ: not earned by their own strength but received through the victory of their representative head. Ephesians 1:11 speaks of believers as having &quot;obtained an inheritance&quot; in Christ — the vocabulary of naḥălâ translated into the NT register.</p>",
"9": "<p>Parenthetical: Hermon&apos;s alternate names among the Sidonians (Sirion) and Amorites (Senir). An administrative note preserving the geographic memory of the conquest. Even in passing details, the narrative bears witness that YHWH&apos;s sovereignty extends over terrain known by the names of pagan peoples — the whole earth belongs to him (Ps 24:1), a confession the NT expresses as Christ&apos;s universal lordship (Col 1:16–17).</p>",
"10": "<p>The full extent of the territory from the plateau cities through Gilead and all Bashan — the comprehensive claim of the promise being fulfilled. The boundary of the inheritance describes what God had committed to give. Every territorial detail in the conquest narrative testifies to God&apos;s precision in keeping covenant promises — a precision the NT claims is displayed ultimately in Christ, in whom every promise of God is yes (2 Cor 1:20).</p>",
"11": "<p>Og king of Bashan — the last of the Rephaim, legendary for his enormous size (his iron bed measured nine cubits by four). The defeat of the Rephaim, the giant remnant associated with primordial opposition to God&apos;s people, carries symbolic weight: God&apos;s people conquer even the seemingly unconquerable. As a shadow: Christ&apos;s defeat of death, &quot;the last enemy&quot; (1 Cor 15:26), fulfills what these giant-slaying episodes anticipate — the ultimate enemy no human power could overcome has been destroyed by God&apos;s representative champion.</p>",
"12": "<p>The Reubenite and Gadite allotment — Moses begins distributing the Transjordanian land as covenant-promised inheritance. As a theme: the God who promises is the God who distributes. The tribal allotments of Deuteronomy and Joshua prefigure the spiritual inheritance distributed to all who are heirs through Christ (Gal 3:29; Rom 8:17 — &quot;fellow heirs with Christ&quot;).</p>",
"13": "<p>Bashan given to the half-tribe of Manasseh — part of the Joseph inheritance, the tribe of the patriarch whose life was shaped by unexpected preservation and redemption from suffering to exaltation. The Manassite allotment in the land captured from Og carries the Joseph typology forward. Christ as the ultimate Joseph figure — betrayed, executed, raised to lordship — ultimately distributes the inheritance he himself secured.</p>",
"14": "<p>Jair the Manassite names the conquered villages after himself — Havvoth-jair. Naming the land enacts ownership; it is the covenantal naming that says &quot;this belongs to us.&quot; In the new creation, the promised inheritance is one where Christ&apos;s name is written on those who receive it (Rev 2:17; 3:12) — the ownership enacted through a new name rather than a place name.</p>",
"15": "<p>&quot;To Machir I gave Gilead.&quot; A brief note establishing inheritance. The covenant God is a distributing God — he gives territory, inheritance, possession. This giving character of YHWH is revealed fully in Christ: &quot;For God so loved the world that he gave&quot; (John 3:16). The greatest giving is not land but the Son himself, through whom all true inheritance is received.</p>",
"16": "<p>The territorial boundaries described precisely — the Arnon Valley, the Jabbok River, the Ammonite border. The precision of the covenant inheritance is a revelation of God&apos;s character: he does not give vaguely but specifically. In Christ, the inheritance is equally precise: resurrection life, adoption as sons, the Holy Spirit as guarantee (Eph 1:13–14). The specificity of the promise is a mark of its trustworthiness.</p>",
"17": "<p>The Arabah and the Jordan as western boundary; the Sea of the Arabah under the slopes of Pisgah. Geographic exactitude in the narrative — the boundary is real territory, not symbolic space. The concreteness of the promised land is the OT foundation for the NT&apos;s equally concrete promises: a bodily resurrection, a renewed earth (Rev 21:1), an inheritance that is &quot;imperishable, undefiled, and unfading&quot; (1 Pet 1:4). The promises are real precisely because YHWH&apos;s covenant has always been embodied and territorial.</p>",
"18": "<p>&quot;The LORD your God has given you this land to possess&quot; — the east-Jordan tribes receive the land but are called to fight for their brothers until everyone has rest. The covenant call to solidarity — those who have received must serve those still waiting to receive — is a theme the NT extends to the whole people of God. &quot;Bear one another&apos;s burdens, and so fulfill the law of Christ&quot; (Gal 6:2). Rest is received together, not hoarded privately.</p>",
"19": "<p>Wives, children, and livestock remain behind — the fighting men cross armed. The separation of those who go forward to battle from those who remain in safety reflects the covenant structure: the representative bears the burden so others can be protected. Christ as the one who goes before his people — &quot;I go to prepare a place for you&quot; (John 14:2) — carries this representative-advance pattern to its ultimate expression.</p>",
"20": "<p>&quot;Until the LORD gives rest to your fellow Israelites as he has given rest to you.&quot; The concept of rest (mĕnûḥâ) is theologically central. Hebrews 3–4 develops the &quot;Sabbath rest&quot; of God as the eschatological inheritance into which Christ leads his people — the rest that Joshua could not fully give (Heb 4:8) because it pointed forward to a greater rest. The Transjordanian tribes who already have rest are the pattern; all Israel entering rest is the type; Christ&apos;s people entering the eternal Sabbath is the fulfillment.</p>",
"21": "<p>&quot;Your eyes have seen everything the LORD your God has done to these two kings. The LORD will do the same to all the kingdoms you are about to enter.&quot; Moses commissions Joshua on the basis of what has already been seen — past faithfulness as the ground for future confidence. In Christ, the resurrection is the already-accomplished act that grounds all future confidence: the one who conquered death will bring his people through every remaining obstacle (1 Cor 15:20–22).</p>",
"22": "<p>&quot;Do not fear them, for the LORD your God himself fights for you.&quot; This verse is Moses&apos;s commissioning word to Joshua, who will face Canaan. It is the assurance that undergirds Joshua&apos;s entire career — and it names Joshua (Yēhôšûaʿ = &quot;YHWH saves&quot;) as the vessel of divine warfare. The name is not incidental: the NT uses the Greek form of this name (Iēsous = Jesus) to identify the one in whom &quot;YHWH saves&quot; is ultimately and perfectly true (Matt 1:21). Joshua types Christ both in name and in this commission to lead the people through fear into rest.</p>",
"23": "<p>Moses pleads with YHWH: &quot;I pleaded with the LORD at that time.&quot; The prayer of Moses at this point reveals the depth of his longing to enter the land — the goal of forty years of leading. That Moses, the great intercessor and mediator of the covenant, is refused entry reveals that no human mediator, however faithful, can bring the people into the fullness of the promise. Only the greater Mediator (1 Tim 2:5; Heb 8:6) can do that.</p>",
"24": "<p>&quot;O Lord GOD, you have only begun to show your servant your greatness and your mighty hand. What god is there in heaven or on earth who can perform deeds and mighty acts like yours?&quot; The incomparability of YHWH — no god in heaven or on earth can match his deeds. This is the exclusive monotheism that the NT expresses Christologically: the incomparable God has acted incomparably in the resurrection of Jesus (Eph 1:19–21 — &quot;the immeasurable greatness of his power... that he worked in Christ when he raised him from the dead&quot;).</p>",
"25": "<p>Moses asks to cross over and see &quot;the good land beyond the Jordan — that good hill country and Lebanon.&quot; The longing for the promised land is among the most poignant moments in all of Scripture. The promised land, with its milk and honey and good hill country, is the concrete shape of covenant blessing. Hebrews 11:16 reads the patriarchal longing for &quot;a better country, that is, a heavenly one&quot; — what Moses sees from Pisgah becomes a shadow of the better country that all of God&apos;s people ultimately seek.</p>",
"26": "<p>&quot;The LORD was angry with me on your account&quot; — Moses bears the consequence of Israel&apos;s rebellion (see Deut 1:37; Num 20:12). Moses is excluded from the inheritance he spent his life moving toward, and this exclusion is explicitly connected to Israel&apos;s sin. This is a shadow of substitutionary consequence: the mediator bears what the people deserved. The contrast with Christ is equally important — Moses bore the consequence (exclusion) without removing the guilt; Christ bore the ultimate consequence (death) and actually removed the sin (Heb 9:26–28).</p>",
"27": "<p>&quot;Go up to the top of Pisgah and look... for you shall not cross this Jordan.&quot; Moses sees the promised land from afar but does not enter. Hebrews 11:13 speaks of the patriarchs who &quot;died in faith, not having received the things promised, but having seen them and greeted them from afar.&quot; Moses sees what he cannot yet receive — a vision of the promise without its possession. In Christ, what is seen from afar is grasped and entered: &quot;the Word became flesh and dwelt among us&quot; (John 1:14) is the promised land becoming present.</p>",
"28": "<p>&quot;Commission Joshua, and encourage him and strengthen him, for he shall cross over at the head of this people and shall lead them to inherit the land you will see.&quot; Joshua is formally commissioned to succeed Moses as the one who will lead Israel into the inheritance. Joshua as type of Christ: he crosses the Jordan (the boundary between wilderness and rest), leads the people into what Moses could not give them, and distributes the inheritance. Hebrews 4:8 makes this typology explicit: &quot;if Joshua had given them rest, God would not have spoken of another day later on&quot; — pointing to Jesus, the greater Joshua, who gives the true Sabbath rest.</p>",
"29": "<p>Israel camps at Beth-peor — the location associated with the Baal Peor apostasy (Num 25; Deut 4:3). Ending the Transjordanian conquest narrative here is not incidental; the narrative places the community at the very site of their greatest recent failure as they prepare to receive Moses&apos;s great covenantal address. As a revelation of God&apos;s mercy: YHWH continues to dwell with and lead his people even in the shadow of their failure. This mercy is the character of God the NT declares fully revealed in Christ (John 1:16–17 — &quot;grace and truth came through Jesus Christ&quot;).</p>"
},
"4": {
"1": "<p>&quot;Listen to the statutes and rules... so that you may live.&quot; Life is conditioned on obedience to the covenant. The law is a life-giving covenant gift — not a burden imposed from outside but the terms of the relationship with the living God. Christ does not abolish this connection between obedience and life; he inhabits it perfectly (Phil 2:8; Heb 5:8–9 — &quot;he learned obedience through what he suffered and, being made perfect, became the source of eternal salvation&quot;). What Israel could not maintain, Christ secured on their behalf.</p>",
"2": "<p>&quot;You shall not add to the word that I command you, nor take from it.&quot; The sufficiency and closure of the revealed covenant word is asserted from Moses forward. In Revelation 22:18–19, the same formula closes the canon of Scripture — John uses identical language to protect the prophetic testimony to Christ. The principle of the sealed word moves from Horeb through the whole canonical tradition to its climax in the testimony to Jesus, the Word made flesh.</p>",
"3": "<p>The lesson of Baal Peor: those who followed the Baal of Peor were destroyed; those who held fast to YHWH are alive. The stark polarity — union with YHWH = life; apostasy = death — is the covenant logic the NT reads as fulfilled in Christ. &quot;In him was life&quot; (John 1:4); &quot;whoever has the Son has life; whoever does not have the Son of God does not have life&quot; (1 John 5:12). The Baal Peor pattern becomes the template for the ultimate choice.</p>",
"4": "<p>&quot;But you who held fast to the LORD your God are all alive today.&quot; The survivors of Baal Peor are identified by their clinging to YHWH (haddĕḇēqîm baYHWH — those who are joined/cleaved to YHWH). This language of adhesion to God is the OT ground for the NT&apos;s union-with-Christ theology. John 15:1–5 (the vine and branches) and Paul&apos;s &quot;in Christ&quot; formula describe the definitive union that makes the believer genuinely alive.</p>",
"5": "<p>Moses teaches the statutes given by YHWH — the teacher-disciple relationship through which the covenant is transmitted. Moses as prophet-teacher is the pattern; Christ as the greater teacher fulfills it (Matt 5:17 — &quot;I have not come to abolish the Law or the Prophets but to fulfill them&quot;; Matt 7:29 — teaching as one having authority, not as the scribes). The Sermon on the Mount is the new Sinai.</p>",
"6": "<p>&quot;Keep and carry out these statutes, for this will be your wisdom and understanding before the other peoples.&quot; The Torah as Israel&apos;s distinctive wisdom among the nations. In Christ, this wisdom is embodied and surpassed: &quot;Christ Jesus, who became to us wisdom from God, righteousness and sanctification and redemption&quot; (1 Cor 1:30). Paul&apos;s theology of Christ-as-wisdom draws directly on the Deuteronomic association of Torah-obedience with wisdom, now transferred to the person of Christ.</p>",
"7": "<p>&quot;What great nation has a god as close to it as the LORD our God is to us whenever we call upon him?&quot; The nearness of YHWH to Israel when they call is the distinctive feature of covenantal relationship. The Incarnation is the definitive answer to this question: God became near in the most literal sense in Jesus (John 1:14 — &quot;the Word became flesh and dwelt [literally, tabernacled] among us&quot;). The proximity YHWH showed in answering prayer has been exceeded by the proximity of God taking flesh.</p>",
"8": "<p>&quot;What great nation has statutes and rules as righteous as this entire law?&quot; The law is righteous — Paul agrees (Rom 7:12: &quot;the law is holy, and the commandment is holy and righteous and good&quot;). The law&apos;s righteousness is not its problem; it cannot produce righteousness in the one who cannot keep it. Christ is &quot;the end of the law for righteousness to everyone who believes&quot; (Rom 10:4) — he fulfills the law&apos;s righteous demand, so that law-righteousness is credited to those in him.</p>",
"9": "<p>&quot;Guard yourselves diligently, lest you forget the things your eyes have seen.&quot; The covenant danger of amnesia — forgetting what God has done is the root of apostasy. The Lord&apos;s Supper (Luke 22:19; 1 Cor 11:24–25) is Christ&apos;s covenant meal instituted specifically &quot;in remembrance of me&quot; — the antidote to spiritual forgetfulness embedded in repeated communal practice. What Deuteronomy commands as vigilance, Christ structures into the regular rhythm of the church&apos;s life.</p>",
"10": "<p>&quot;The day you stood before the LORD your God at Horeb&quot; — the Sinai assembly where Israel heard God&apos;s voice from fire. Hebrews 12:18–24 explicitly contrasts the Sinai assembly with the assembly of the church at Zion: &quot;you have not come to what may be touched, a blazing fire... but you have come to Mount Zion... and to Jesus, the mediator of a new covenant.&quot; The Sinai assembly is the type; the assembly of the church gathered to Christ is the fulfillment.</p>",
"11": "<p>The mountain burns with fire, wrapped in darkness, cloud, and deep gloom. The terror of the Sinai theophany — the unapproachable holiness of God — is the OT baseline. Hebrews 12:21 notes that even Moses said, &quot;I tremble with fear.&quot; The contrast the NT draws is not that God&apos;s holiness has been softened, but that in Christ we have a Mediator who makes approach possible: &quot;we have confidence to enter the holy places by the blood of Jesus&quot; (Heb 10:19).</p>",
"12": "<p>&quot;You heard the sound of words but saw no form — there was only a voice.&quot; The aniconic Horeb theophany — God revealed in word without visible form — grounds the prohibition of images. The paradox the NT presents is that &quot;no one has ever seen God; the only God, who is at the Father&apos;s side, he has made him known&quot; (John 1:18). The formlessness of Horeb anticipates the unique visibility of God in Christ: the invisible God becomes visible not in an idol but in the Son, who is &quot;the image [εἰκών] of the invisible God&quot; (Col 1:15). Direct Christological connection.</p>",
"13": "<p>The covenant declared at Horeb — the Ten Commandments written on two tablets of stone. The law on stone is external, imposed on the people without being internalized. Jeremiah 31:33 (the new covenant) and Ezekiel 36:26 (heart of flesh replacing the heart of stone) promise what the Horeb tablets could not accomplish. In Christ, this new covenant is enacted (Luke 22:20: &quot;This cup is the new covenant in my blood&quot;) and the Spirit is given to write the law on the heart (2 Cor 3:3 — &quot;not on tablets of stone but on tablets of human hearts&quot;). The Horeb tablets are the type; the Spirit-written heart is the fulfillment.</p>",
"14": "<p>Moses is commanded to teach statutes and rules for the land. The Moses-as-teacher/lawgiver pattern is the OT template for prophetic authority. Jesus explicitly situates himself in relation to Moses: &quot;You have heard that it was said... but I say to you&quot; (Matt 5:21–48) — not abolishing Moses but speaking with a greater authority than Moses. The one who gives the law at Sinai through Moses speaks the law directly from himself in the Sermon on the Mount.</p>",
"15": "<p>&quot;Watch yourselves very carefully. Since you saw no form on the day the LORD spoke to you at Horeb.&quot; The call to caution is grounded in the formless nature of the Horeb revelation: because God appeared without a form, no form can adequately represent him. The Incarnation is not a violation of this principle but its fulfillment: God himself chose the one form in which his invisible nature could be visible, the human form of the Son (John 14:9 — &quot;Whoever has seen me has seen the Father&quot;). The prohibition of human-made images does not prohibit the God-given image.</p>",
"16": "<p>&quot;Do not act corruptly by making for yourselves a carved image in the form of any figure — the likeness of male or female.&quot; The prohibition of human images. The irony of idolatry is that humanity, made in God&apos;s image (Gen 1:26), begins making God in humanity&apos;s image — a reversal of the proper order. Romans 1:23 identifies this as the fundamental exchange: &quot;they exchanged the glory of the immortal God for images resembling mortal man.&quot; Christ restores the proper order: in him, the invisible God is imaged without human manufacture.</p>",
"17": "<p>The prohibition of animal images — any winged bird. The comprehensive list (vv.16–18) moves from human to animal to bird to reptile to fish, covering the entire created order. This follows the order of creation (Gen 1) in reverse, making the point: no created thing is an appropriate image for the Creator. The NT extension: &quot;they worshiped and served the creature rather than the Creator&quot; (Rom 1:25). In Christ, the Creator himself enters creation as the definitive self-disclosure.</p>",
"18": "<p>The prohibition of creeping things and fish images — completing the comprehensive sweep of the created order. No creature, however humble or exalted, can bear the weight of representing YHWH. This theology of incomparability prepares for the NT claim that only the Son, who is in the very form of God (Phil 2:6, morphē theou), can image the Father — and only because he is not a creature but the Creator.</p>",
"19": "<p>&quot;Beware lest you... be drawn away to bow down and serve&quot; the heavenly bodies, which YHWH &quot;allotted to all the peoples under the whole heaven.&quot; The nations worshipped what God allotted to them as created order; Israel was called to worship the Creator directly. Paul&apos;s Areopagus speech (Acts 17:26–31) adapts this logic: the nations operated in ignorance of the true God who &quot;made from one man every nation&quot; and &quot;allotted periods and boundaries.&quot; In Christ, all nations are called to repent and worship the Creator rather than his creatures.</p>",
"20": "<p>&quot;The LORD has taken you and brought you out of the iron furnace, out of Egypt, to be a people belonging to his own inheritance.&quot; The iron furnace (kûr habbarzel) as metaphor for Egyptian slavery — the refining fire of suffering that produces the people of God. The Exodus is the primary redemption type. The NT presents Christ&apos;s death and resurrection as the new Exodus: Luke 9:31 describes the Transfiguration as Jesus speaking of his &quot;departure,&quot; the Greek word being ἔξοδον — his exodus, accomplished at Jerusalem. The people are brought out of a worse bondage through a greater deliverance.</p>",
"21": "<p>&quot;The LORD was angry with me on your account.&quot; Moses is excluded from the land he spent his life working toward, and this exclusion is explicitly because of what Israel did (Deut 1:37; Num 20:12). The mediator bears the consequence of the people&apos;s sin — a shadow of substitutionary suffering. The contrast with Christ is essential: Moses bore exclusion without removing the guilt; Christ bore death and removed the sin itself. &quot;He himself bore our sins in his body on the tree&quot; (1 Pet 2:24) — not merely sharing the consequence but defeating its cause.</p>",
"22": "<p>&quot;I must die in this land; I am not to cross the Jordan. But you shall cross over and possess that good land.&quot; Moses dies so that the people can continue into what he cannot reach. The pattern of the leader dying on behalf of the mission&apos;s continuation is a shadow. Christ&apos;s death is not a failure that others must compensate for but the very means of the mission&apos;s accomplishment: &quot;It is to your advantage that I go away&quot; (John 16:7). Moses&apos;s death is the shadow; Christ&apos;s death is the substance.</p>",
"23": "<p>&quot;Be careful not to forget the covenant of the LORD your God.&quot; The danger of forgetting the covenant is the central concern of Deuteronomy. The new covenant addresses this at its root: &quot;I will put my law within them, and I will write it on their hearts&quot; (Jer 31:33). What Deuteronomy must command as vigilance, the new covenant promises as transformation. Christ is the mediator of this new covenant (Heb 9:15), in whom what was inscribed on stone becomes written on the heart by the Spirit.</p>",
"24": "<p>&quot;For the LORD your God is a consuming fire, a jealous God.&quot; This is directly cited in Hebrews 12:29: &quot;for our God is a consuming fire,&quot; placed there after the exhortation to worship God acceptably with reverence and awe (12:28). The consuming fire of God&apos;s holiness is not abolished in the new covenant — but now mediated through Christ&apos;s blood, which speaks &quot;a better word than the blood of Abel&quot; (Heb 12:24). The fire remains; access is through the Mediator. Direct NT citation.</p>",
"25": "<p>The warning against idolatry in future generations — when Israel has grown comfortable in the land and acts corruptly. The covenant anticipates its own violation, which is both prophetic realism and a demonstration that the old covenant was never adequate to ensure obedience. The new covenant promise (Jer 31:31–34) addresses this inadequacy directly: &quot;Not like the covenant that I made with their fathers... my covenant that they broke.&quot; Christ establishes the covenant that cannot be broken by human failure.</p>",
"26": "<p>&quot;I call heaven and earth as witnesses against you today.&quot; The cosmic covenant lawsuit (rîb) structure — heaven and earth as witnesses to covenant violation — is an ANE suzerainty-treaty convention Deuteronomy deploys. The same cosmic witness structure appears in Revelation, where the heavenly court evaluates the nations. In Christ, the cosmic lawsuit is resolved not by condemnation of the covenant-breaker but by the covenant-keeper bearing the verdict: &quot;There is therefore now no condemnation for those who are in Christ Jesus&quot; (Rom 8:1).</p>",
"27": "<p>&quot;The LORD will scatter you among the peoples.&quot; The exile sanction is the covenant&apos;s ultimate consequence for sustained unfaithfulness. The Babylonian exile fulfilled this warning precisely. The NT counter-movement is the gathering of the scattered: &quot;he would gather into one the children of God who are scattered abroad&quot; (John 11:52). Christ&apos;s death is the gathering act that reverses the exile-scattering sanction of the covenant.</p>",
"28": "<p>&quot;There you will serve gods made by human hands — wood and stone — that can neither see, nor hear, nor eat, nor smell.&quot; The exile ironically fulfills what the people chose: they preferred idols to YHWH, so they are given idols as their gods. The biblical polemic against idols (Ps 115:4–7; Isa 44:9–20) culminates in Paul&apos;s exposition in Rom 1:23 and Acts 17:29 — &quot;we ought not to think that the divine being is like gold or silver or stone, an image formed by the art and imagination of man.&quot; In Christ, the living God who is &quot;not far from each one of us&quot; (Acts 17:27) is revealed, ending the futility of idol worship.</p>",
"29": "<p>&quot;But from there you will seek the LORD your God and you will find him, if you search for him with all your heart and with all your soul.&quot; The promise of finding God in the midst of exile — the God who disciplines is the God who can be found. In Christ, seeking God is both enabled and guaranteed: &quot;Seek and you will find; knock, and it will be opened to you&quot; (Matt 7:7). The Deuteronomic promise of finding God beyond exile becomes the gospel promise of access to the Father through the Son.</p>",
"30": "<p>&quot;In the latter days you will return to the LORD your God and listen to his voice.&quot; The phrase &quot;latter days&quot; (ʾaḥărît hayyāmîm) is an eschatological formula — the prophets use it for the messianic age. Hebrews 1:2 opens: &quot;In these last days he has spoken to us by his Son&quot; — the claim that the &quot;latter days&quot; anticipated in Deuteronomy have arrived in the Christ event. The return to YHWH in the latter days is the repentance and faith that the gospel announces as now available. Direct eschatological connection.</p>",
"31": "<p>&quot;For the LORD your God is a merciful God. He will not abandon you or destroy you or forget the covenant with your fathers.&quot; The divine mercy (raḥûm) that grounds restoration after exile is the character of God. Romans 5:8 presents this mercy concretely and finally: &quot;God demonstrates his own love for us in this: while we were still sinners, Christ died for us.&quot; The mercy that preserved Israel through exile is the same mercy that sent the Son — the character of God displayed in both covenant histories.</p>",
"32": "<p>&quot;Has any such great thing as this ever happened, or has anything like it been heard of?&quot; The rhetoric of incomparability — the Exodus is presented as an event without parallel in human history. No other nation heard the voice of God from fire or was rescued from inside another nation by divine intervention. The NT makes a parallel incomparability claim about the resurrection: &quot;the immeasurable greatness of his power toward us who believe, according to the working of his great might that he worked in Christ when he raised him from the dead&quot; (Eph 1:19–20). The incomparable God has acted incomparably again.</p>",
"33": "<p>&quot;Did any people ever hear the voice of God speaking out of the midst of fire, as you have heard, and survive?&quot; Hearing the voice of God from fire and surviving is presented as the unique privilege of Israel at Sinai. In the New Testament, the voice of the Son is the voice of God in an even more direct sense: &quot;My sheep hear my voice&quot; (John 10:27); &quot;the hour is coming, and is now here, when the dead will hear the voice of the Son of God, and those who hear will live&quot; (John 5:25). The fire-voice of Sinai becomes the life-giving voice of the Son.</p>",
"34": "<p>&quot;Or has any god ever attempted to go and take one nation out of the midst of another nation — by tests, by signs and wonders, by war, by a mighty hand and an outstretched arm?&quot; This is the Deuteronomic catalog of divine action in the Exodus. The five-fold description becomes the template for the Passover Haggadah and the NT&apos;s own catalog of salvation: God acts through testing, signs, wonders, power, and display of strength — culminating in the resurrection, which the NT describes in precisely these terms (Acts 2:22; Eph 1:19–21).</p>",
"35": "<p>&quot;To you it was shown so that you would know that the LORD is God; there is no other besides him&quot; — the exclusive monotheism formula: ʾên ʿôd, &quot;there is no other.&quot; This is the theological bedrock on which Paul builds in 1 Corinthians 8:4–6, where he distinguishes &quot;one God, the Father, from whom are all things&quot; and &quot;one Lord, Jesus Christ, through whom are all things.&quot; Paul christologically differentiates the ʾên ʿôd — the one God is now confessed as Father and Son — without abandoning the exclusive monotheism Deuteronomy established.</p>",
"36": "<p>&quot;Out of heaven he let you hear his voice to discipline you.&quot; The heavenly voice at Sinai disciplines Israel into covenant knowledge. In the Gospel of John (12:28–30), the Father&apos;s voice comes from heaven again — the crowd hears thunder, some say an angel has spoken, but Jesus says the voice came for their sake. The pattern of divine voice from heaven recurs and concentrates on Christ, who is himself the Word (John 1:1) that the heavenly voice attests.</p>",
"37": "<p>&quot;Because he loved your fathers and chose their descendants after them, he brought you out of Egypt himself, with his great power.&quot; The Exodus is rooted in electing love — because YHWH loved the patriarchs, he acts for their descendants. This is the OT ground of election theology that Paul develops in Romans 9–11 and Ephesians 1. The love that chose Abraham and acted in the Exodus is the same love that predestined believers to adoption through Jesus Christ (Eph 1:4–5).</p>",
"38": "<p>&quot;To drive out before you nations greater and mightier than you, to bring you in and give you their land as an inheritance.&quot; The divine pattern: God drives out, God brings in, God gives as inheritance. Believers receive an inheritance not of land but of the fullness of Christ: &quot;all things are yours... and you are Christ&apos;s, and Christ is God&apos;s&quot; (1 Cor 3:21–23). The language of inheritance — naḥălâ — reaches its NT fullness in Romans 8:17 and Ephesians 1:11.</p>",
"39": "<p>&quot;Know therefore today... that the LORD is God in heaven above and on the earth beneath — there is no other.&quot; The climactic declaration of Deuteronomic monotheism — not just the ʾên ʿôd formula but its cosmic scope: in heaven above and on earth beneath, there is only YHWH. The New Testament confesses this same exclusive lordship of Christ: &quot;God has highly exalted him and bestowed on him the name that is above every name, so that at the name of Jesus every knee should bow, in heaven and on earth and under the earth&quot; (Phil 2:9–10 — a direct echo of &quot;in heaven above and on earth beneath&quot;). Direct christological connection.</p>",
"40": "<p>&quot;Keep his statutes and commandments... so that it may go well with you and with your children after you, and so that you may live long in the land.&quot; The covenant blessing for obedience. Christ, the perfectly obedient son (Heb 5:8 — &quot;although he was a Son, he learned obedience through what he suffered&quot;), earns what Israel could not maintain. The blessing of complete covenant faithfulness accrues to those &quot;in Christ&quot; through his obedience imputed to them — the obedience the law demanded, Christ supplied (Rom 5:19).</p>",
"41": "<p>Moses sets apart three cities of refuge east of the Jordan. The cities of refuge are a type of Christ: the place where the manslayer (anyone who causes death, intentionally or not — and by extension, all of humanity implicated in sin and death) can flee from the avenger of blood. Hebrews 6:18 explicitly uses the &quot;fled for refuge&quot; language for the hope believers seize in Christ: &quot;we who have fled for refuge might have strong encouragement to hold fast to the hope set before us.&quot; Direct typological connection.</p>",
"42": "<p>The city of refuge receives the manslayer who &quot;kills his neighbor unintentionally without prior enmity&quot; — accidental killing, not murder. The city protects while the legal process works. The type: Christ receives the guilty who flee to him, providing shelter from the consequences of sin. Numbers 35:25 specifies that the manslayer must remain in the city of refuge until the death of the high priest — then he is free. The death of Christ, the great High Priest (Heb 4:14), is the event that sets the refugee free permanently.</p>",
"43": "<p>The three cities named: Bezer, Ramoth, and Golan — one in each Transjordanian territory. The geographic distribution ensures access: no one is too far from refuge. The accessibility of the cities of refuge typifies the accessibility of Christ: &quot;everyone who calls on the name of the Lord will be saved&quot; (Rom 10:13, citing Joel 2:32). The Gospel&apos;s universal offer — that no one is geographically or socially beyond reach of the refuge in Christ — is prepared for by the three distributed cities.</p>",
"44": "<p>&quot;This is the law that Moses set before the people of Israel.&quot; The formal superscription to the Deuteronomic law-code. Moses sets the law &quot;before&quot; the people — the imagery of placement, a treaty document presented to the vassal. Christ comes not to set aside the law but to fulfill it from within it (Matt 5:17). The law Moses placed before Israel is the same law Christ embodies and fulfills — &quot;he is the end of the law for righteousness to everyone who believes&quot; (Rom 10:4).</p>",
"45": "<p>&quot;These are the testimonies, the statutes, and the rules that Moses spoke to the Israelites.&quot; The three-fold description of the law — testimonies (ʿēdôt), statutes (ḥuqqîm), and rules (mišpāṭîm) — covers its scope comprehensively: what witnesses to God&apos;s character, what regulates behavior, and what governs justice. Christ fulfills all three: he is the testimony to God (John 14:9), the pattern of holy behavior (1 Pet 2:21), and the just judge (Acts 17:31). The law&apos;s fullness is met in the fullness of Christ.</p>",
"46": "<p>The location: east of the Jordan in the valley opposite Beth-peor. The site of Moses&apos;s final teaching is associated both with the conquest of Sihon and with the Baal Peor apostasy. The law is given in the shadow of both victory and failure — the two poles of Israel&apos;s story. The Gospel likewise comes to a humanity marked by both God&apos;s image (victory, dignity) and sin (failure, death). Christ addresses the whole of the human condition, not only its aspirational heights.</p>",
"47": "<p>&quot;They had taken possession of his land and the land of Og king of Bashan — the two Amorite kings east of the Jordan.&quot; The summary of the Transjordanian victories frames the legal material that follows. The conquest was real and complete; the law is given to a people who have already experienced divine faithfulness in battle. The Gospel similarly does not come to an audience with no history — it comes to a world that has already seen God&apos;s faithfulness across the entire OT story. Christ is the telos of that story (Luke 24:27).</p>",
"48": "<p>The geographic boundaries extending from Aroer to Mount Sirion (Hermon). The careful notation of territorial boundaries is the narrative&apos;s way of saying: the promises were real, the land is specific, the fulfillment is concrete. The NT inheritance in Christ is equally concrete: a bodily resurrection, a renewed creation (Rom 8:21; Rev 21:1), a city with specific dimensions (Rev 21:15–17). Biblical hope is always embodied and specific, never merely spiritual in the Greek sense.</p>",
"49": "<p>The Arabah east of the Jordan, under the slopes of Pisgah — the final geographic boundary note before the Deuteronomic law-code begins in chapter 5. From Pisgah, Moses will later view the land he cannot enter (Deut 34:1). The final boundary note points toward that final scene of Moses at Pisgah, seeing what he could not receive. Christ receives what Moses saw and could not enter — and opens it to all who follow him. He is the pioneer and perfecter of faith (Heb 12:2), crossing every Pisgah on behalf of those who follow.</p>"
}
}

